      "content": "<h2>Who was Isaac Newton?</h2><p>Sir Isaac Newton (1643-1727) was an English mathematician and physicist. In 1687, he published his famous book <em>Principia Mathematica</em>, which contains his three laws of motion that form the foundation of classical mechanics.</p><h2>Newton's First Law of Motion (Law of Inertia)</h2><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Statement:</strong> An object at rest stays at rest, and an object in motion stays in motion at constant velocity, unless acted upon by an external unbalanced force.</div><h3>Key Concept: Inertia</h3><p><strong>Inertia</strong> is the tendency of an object to resist changes in its state of motion. Heavier objects have more inertia than lighter objects.</p><p><strong>Real-life Examples:</strong></p><ul><li>🚗 When a car suddenly brakes, passengers jerk forward — their bodies want to keep moving</li><li>📚 A book on a table stays there until you push it</li><li>🏈 A football keeps rolling until friction stops it</li></ul><h2>Newton's Second Law of Motion</h2><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Statement:</strong> The acceleration of an object is directly proportional to the net force acting on it and inversely proportional to its mass.</div><div class='fact-box'><strong>Formula: F = ma</strong><br><br>Where: F = Force (in Newtons), m = mass (in kg), a = acceleration (in m/s²)</div><h3>Understanding F = ma</h3><ul><li>If you double the force → acceleration doubles</li><li>If you double the mass → acceleration halves</li></ul><p><strong>Example:</strong> If you push a 5 kg box with 20 N force:<br>Acceleration = F/m = 20/5 = <strong>4 m/s²</strong></p><table><tr><th>Force (N)</th><th>Mass (kg)</th><th>Acceleration (m/s²)</th></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>2</td><td>5</td></tr><tr><td>20</td><td>4</td><td>5</td></tr><tr><td>30</td><td>5</td><td>6</td></tr></table><h2>Newton's Third Law of Motion</h2><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Statement:</strong> For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.</div><p><strong>Real-life Examples:</strong></p><ul><li>🚀 <strong>Rocket Propulsion:</strong> Gas expelled downward (action) → rocket moves upward (reaction)</li><li>🏊 <strong>Swimming:</strong> Hands push water backward (action) → body moves forward (reaction)</li><li>🔫 <strong>Gun Recoil:</strong> Bullet fires forward (action) → gun kicks backward (reaction)</li><li>🐟 <strong>Fish Swimming:</strong> Fins push water back → fish moves forward</li></ul><h2>Quick Comparison Table</h2><table><tr><th>Law</th><th>Key Word</th><th>Formula</th></tr><tr><td>First Law</td><td>Inertia</td><td>F = 0 → a = 0</td></tr><tr><td>Second Law</td><td>Force</td><td>F = ma</td></tr><tr><td>Third Law</td><td>Action-Reaction</td><td>F₁ = -F₂</td></tr></table><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Exam Tip:</strong> Always remember — Third Law forces act on DIFFERENT objects, not the same object. Action and reaction are always equal in magnitude but opposite in direction.</div>",
      "content_hi": "<h2>न्यूटन के गति के नियम</h2><p>सर आइज़क न्यूटन ने 1687 में गति के तीन नियम दिए जो आज भी भौतिकी की नींव हैं।</p><h2>पहला नियम (जड़त्व का नियम)</h2><div class='highlight-box'><strong>कथन:</strong> कोई वस्तु तब तक अपनी स्थिति नहीं बदलती जब तक उस पर कोई बाहरी बल न लगे।</div><h2>दूसरा नियम</h2><div class='fact-box'><strong>सूत्र: F = ma</strong><br>जहाँ F = बल, m = द्रव्यमान, a = त्वरण</div><h2>तीसरा नियम</h2><div class='highlight-box'><strong>कथन:</strong> प्रत्येक क्रिया की समान और विपरीत प्रतिक्रिया होती है।</div>"
