      "content": "<h2>Introduction to Tenses</h2><p>Tenses indicate the <strong>time of an action</strong> in a sentence. There are three main tenses in English: <strong>Present, Past, and Future</strong>. Each has four forms, making a total of <strong>12 tenses</strong>.</p><h2>Present Tense (4 Types)</h2><h3>1. Simple Present Tense</h3><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Structure:</strong> Subject + V1 (s/es for he/she/it)<br><strong>Example:</strong> She <em>reads</em> books every day.</div><p><strong>Uses:</strong> Habits, general truths, facts</p><h3>2. Present Continuous Tense</h3><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Structure:</strong> Subject + is/am/are + V-ing<br><strong>Example:</strong> She <em>is reading</em> a book right now.</div><p><strong>Uses:</strong> Actions happening right now</p><h3>3. Present Perfect Tense</h3><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Structure:</strong> Subject + has/have + V3<br><strong>Example:</strong> She <em>has read</em> this book before.</div><h3>4. Present Perfect Continuous</h3><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Structure:</strong> Subject + has/have + been + V-ing<br><strong>Example:</strong> She <em>has been reading</em> for 2 hours.</div><h2>Past Tense (4 Types)</h2><table><tr><th>Tense</th><th>Structure</th><th>Example</th></tr><tr><td>Simple Past</td><td>Subject + V2</td><td>She <em>read</em> a book.</td></tr><tr><td>Past Continuous</td><td>Subject + was/were + V-ing</td><td>She <em>was reading</em>.</td></tr><tr><td>Past Perfect</td><td>Subject + had + V3</td><td>She <em>had read</em> it.</td></tr><tr><td>Past Perfect Continuous</td><td>Subject + had been + V-ing</td><td>She <em>had been reading</em>.</td></tr></table><h2>Future Tense (4 Types)</h2><table><tr><th>Tense</th><th>Structure</th><th>Example</th></tr><tr><td>Simple Future</td><td>Subject + will + V1</td><td>She <em>will read</em> it.</td></tr><tr><td>Future Continuous</td><td>Subject + will be + V-ing</td><td>She <em>will be reading</em>.</td></tr><tr><td>Future Perfect</td><td>Subject + will have + V3</td><td>She <em>will have read</em> it.</td></tr><tr><td>Future Perfect Continuous</td><td>Subject + will have been + V-ing</td><td>She <em>will have been reading</em>.</td></tr></table><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Memory Trick:</strong> V1 = Base form (go), V2 = Past form (went), V3 = Past Participle (gone)</div><h2>Quick Revision Notes</h2><ul><li>Read the definition and write it once in your own words.</li><li>Make a small table of key facts, formulas, dates, or examples related to English Grammar: All 12 Tenses Explained with Examples.</li><li>Revise the topic after 24 hours and again before the exam.</li></ul><h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2><ul><li>Do not memorize only headings; understand the reason behind every point.</li><li>Do not mix similar terms, dates, examples, or formulas.</li><li>Do not skip practice questions after reading the explanation.</li></ul><h2>Practice Questions</h2><ol><li>Write a short note on the main idea of this topic.</li><li>List three important facts that can be asked in exams.</li><li>Explain one example in simple language.</li><li>Create five one-line revision points from this article.</li></ol><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><h3>Is this topic important for exams?</h3><p>Yes. This topic is useful for school tests, revision, and competitive exam general awareness depending on the syllabus.</p><h3>How should I revise it quickly?</h3><p>Start with the summary, then revise the table or bullet points, and finally solve two or three practice questions.</p>",
