      "content": "<h2>What is the Periodic Table?</h2><p>The Periodic Table is an organized arrangement of all known <strong>118 chemical elements</strong> based on their atomic number, electron configuration, and chemical properties. It was developed by <strong>Dmitri Mendeleev</strong> in 1869.</p><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Modern Periodic Law:</strong> Properties of elements are a periodic function of their atomic numbers.</div><h2>Structure of the Periodic Table</h2><h3>Periods (Horizontal Rows)</h3><p>There are <strong>7 periods</strong> in the Periodic Table. Each period represents a new electron shell.</p><table><tr><th>Period</th><th>Elements</th><th>Shells</th></tr><tr><td>Period 1</td><td>2 elements (H, He)</td><td>1 shell</td></tr><tr><td>Period 2</td><td>8 elements (Li to Ne)</td><td>2 shells</td></tr><tr><td>Period 3</td><td>8 elements (Na to Ar)</td><td>3 shells</td></tr><tr><td>Period 4</td><td>18 elements</td><td>4 shells</td></tr></table><h3>Groups (Vertical Columns)</h3><p>There are <strong>18 groups</strong>. Elements in the same group have similar chemical properties.</p><ul><li><strong>Group 1:</strong> Alkali Metals (Li, Na, K, Rb, Cs, Fr)</li><li><strong>Group 2:</strong> Alkaline Earth Metals (Be, Mg, Ca, Sr, Ba, Ra)</li><li><strong>Group 17:</strong> Halogens (F, Cl, Br, I, At)</li><li><strong>Group 18:</strong> Noble Gases (He, Ne, Ar, Kr, Xe, Rn)</li></ul><h2>Memory Tricks</h2><div class='fact-box'><strong>First 20 Elements Trick:</strong><br>H He Li Be B C N O F Ne Na Mg Al Si P S Cl Ar K Ca<br><br><em>\"HaHa LiBe BCN OF NeNa MgAlSi PS ClAr KCa\"</em></div><h2>Important Properties</h2><table><tr><th>Property</th><th>Across Period (→)</th><th>Down Group (↓)</th></tr><tr><td>Atomic Size</td><td>Decreases</td><td>Increases</td></tr><tr><td>Metallic Character</td><td>Decreases</td><td>Increases</td></tr><tr><td>Electronegativity</td><td>Increases</td><td>Decreases</td></tr><tr><td>Ionization Energy</td><td>Increases</td><td>Decreases</td></tr></table><h2>Quick Revision Notes</h2><ul><li>Read the definition and write it once in your own words.</li><li>Make a small table of key facts, formulas, dates, or examples related to Periodic Table: Elements, Groups and Properties Explained.</li><li>Revise the topic after 24 hours and again before the exam.</li></ul><h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2><ul><li>Do not memorize only headings; understand the reason behind every point.</li><li>Do not mix similar terms, dates, examples, or formulas.</li><li>Do not skip practice questions after reading the explanation.</li></ul><h2>Practice Questions</h2><ol><li>Write a short note on the main idea of this topic.</li><li>List three important facts that can be asked in exams.</li><li>Explain one example in simple language.</li><li>Create five one-line revision points from this article.</li></ol><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><h3>Is this topic important for exams?</h3><p>Yes. This topic is useful for school tests, revision, and competitive exam general awareness depending on the syllabus.</p><h3>How should I revise it quickly?</h3><p>Start with the summary, then revise the table or bullet points, and finally solve two or three practice questions.</p>",
