      "content": "<h2>What are Fractions?</h2><p>A fraction represents a <strong>part of a whole</strong>. It has two parts: <strong>Numerator</strong> (top number) and <strong>Denominator</strong> (bottom number).</p><div class='fact-box'><strong>Example:</strong> In the fraction 3/4 → Numerator = 3, Denominator = 4<br>This means 3 parts out of 4 equal parts.</div><h2>Types of Fractions</h2><table><tr><th>Type</th><th>Definition</th><th>Example</th></tr><tr><td>Proper Fraction</td><td>Numerator less than denominator</td><td>3/4, 2/5</td></tr><tr><td>Improper Fraction</td><td>Numerator greater than denominator</td><td>5/3, 7/4</td></tr><tr><td>Mixed Number</td><td>Whole number + proper fraction</td><td>2½, 3¾</td></tr><tr><td>Like Fractions</td><td>Same denominator</td><td>1/4, 3/4</td></tr><tr><td>Unlike Fractions</td><td>Different denominators</td><td>1/3, 1/4</td></tr></table><h2>Converting Between Fractions, Decimals and Percentages</h2><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Fraction → Decimal:</strong> Divide numerator by denominator<br>3/4 = 3 ÷ 4 = 0.75<br><br><strong>Decimal → Percentage:</strong> Multiply by 100<br>0.75 × 100 = 75%<br><br><strong>Percentage → Fraction:</strong> Divide by 100<br>75% = 75/100 = 3/4</div><h2>Important Percentage Formulas</h2><ul><li>Percentage of a number: (Percentage × Number) / 100</li><li>Percentage increase: [(New - Old) / Old] × 100</li><li>Percentage decrease: [(Old - New) / Old] × 100</li></ul><div class='fact-box'><strong>Common Fraction-Decimal-Percentage Table:</strong><table><tr><th>Fraction</th><th>Decimal</th><th>Percentage</th></tr><tr><td>1/2</td><td>0.5</td><td>50%</td></tr><tr><td>1/4</td><td>0.25</td><td>25%</td></tr><tr><td>3/4</td><td>0.75</td><td>75%</td></tr><tr><td>1/3</td><td>0.333</td><td>33.3%</td></tr><tr><td>1/5</td><td>0.2</td><td>20%</td></tr></table></div><h2>Quick Revision Notes</h2><ul><li>Read the definition and write it once in your own words.</li><li>Make a small table of key facts, formulas, dates, or examples related to Fractions, Decimals and Percentages: Complete Math Guide.</li><li>Revise the topic after 24 hours and again before the exam.</li></ul><h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2><ul><li>Do not memorize only headings; understand the reason behind every point.</li><li>Do not mix similar terms, dates, examples, or formulas.</li><li>Do not skip practice questions after reading the explanation.</li></ul><h2>Practice Questions</h2><ol><li>Write a short note on the main idea of this topic.</li><li>List three important facts that can be asked in exams.</li><li>Explain one example in simple language.</li><li>Create five one-line revision points from this article.</li></ol><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><h3>Is this topic important for exams?</h3><p>Yes. This topic is useful for school tests, revision, and competitive exam general awareness depending on the syllabus.</p><h3>How should I revise it quickly?</h3><p>Start with the summary, then revise the table or bullet points, and finally solve two or three practice questions.</p>",
      "content_hi": "<h2>भिन्न (Fractions)</h2><p>भिन्न किसी पूर्ण वस्तु के एक भाग को दर्शाता है। इसमें अंश (ऊपर) और हर (नीचे) होते हैं।</p><h2>रूपांतरण (Conversion)</h2><div class='highlight-box'>भिन्न → दशमलव: अंश को हर से भाग दें<br>प्रतिशत → भिन्न: 100 से भाग दें</div>"
