      "content": "<h2>Why Reasoning is Important?</h2><p>Reasoning section is asked in almost all competitive exams — SSC, Banking, Railway, Police, UPSC. It tests your <strong>logical thinking and problem-solving</strong> ability. With proper tricks, you can solve questions in 10-15 seconds!</p><h2>1. Number Series</h2><p>Find the missing number by identifying the pattern.</p><div class='fact-box'><strong>Common Patterns:</strong><ul><li>+2, +4, +6, +8... (increasing difference)</li><li>×2, ×3, ×4... (multiplication series)</li><li>Prime numbers: 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13...</li><li>Perfect squares: 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36...</li><li>Fibonacci: 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13...</li></ul></div><h2>2. Coding-Decoding</h2><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Trick:</strong> If A=1, B=2... Z=26, then:<br>FACE → 6+1+3+5 = 15<br><br>Position Reverse: Z=1, Y=2... A=26<br>Opposite Letter: A↔Z, B↔Y, C↔X (add up to 27)</div><h2>3. Blood Relations</h2><p>Draw a family tree to solve easily:</p><ul><li>Son's son = Grandson</li><li>Brother's daughter = Niece</li><li>Mother's brother = Maternal Uncle (Mama)</li><li>Father's sister = Paternal Aunt (Bua/Phuphi)</li><li>Mother's sister = Maternal Aunt (Mausi)</li></ul><h2>4. Direction Test</h2><div class='fact-box'><strong>Important Rule:</strong><br>After rotating Right (clockwise): North→East→South→West<br>After rotating Left (anti-clockwise): North→West→South→East<br><br>Shadow Direction: Morning shadow = West, Evening shadow = East, Noon shadow = North</div><h2>5. Analogy</h2><p>Find the relationship between the first pair and apply it to the second pair.</p><table><tr><th>Example</th><th>Relationship</th></tr><tr><td>Doctor : Hospital :: Teacher : ?</td><td>Place of work → School</td></tr><tr><td>Book : Library :: Painting : ?</td><td>Place of storage → Museum/Gallery</td></tr><tr><td>Fish : Water :: Bird : ?</td><td>Natural habitat → Air/Sky</td></tr></table><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Golden Rule:</strong> In Reasoning, always attempt questions you are 100% sure of first. Don't waste time on tricky questions in the exam.</div><h2>Quick Revision Notes</h2><ul><li>Read the definition and write it once in your own words.</li><li>Make a small table of key facts, formulas, dates, or examples related to Reasoning Tricks and Shortcuts for All Competitive Exams.</li><li>Revise the topic after 24 hours and again before the exam.</li></ul><h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2><ul><li>Do not memorize only headings; understand the reason behind every point.</li><li>Do not mix similar terms, dates, examples, or formulas.</li><li>Do not skip practice questions after reading the explanation.</li></ul><h2>Practice Questions</h2><ol><li>Write a short note on the main idea of this topic.</li><li>List three important facts that can be asked in exams.</li><li>Explain one example in simple language.</li><li>Create five one-line revision points from this article.</li></ol><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><h3>Is this topic important for exams?</h3><p>Yes. This topic is useful for school tests, revision, and competitive exam general awareness depending on the syllabus.</p><h3>How should I revise it quickly?</h3><p>Start with the summary, then revise the table or bullet points, and finally solve two or three practice questions.</p>",
      "content_hi": "<h2>रीजनिंग में सफलता के टिप्स</h2><p>रीजनिंग में सही तकनीक से कठिन प्रश्न भी आसान हो जाते हैं।</p><h2>संख्या श्रेणी के नियम</h2><div class='fact-box'>+2, +4, +6 (बढ़ता अंतर) | ×2, ×3 (गुणन) | अभाज्य संख्याएं | वर्ग संख्याएं</div>"
