      "content": "<h2>Introduction to Mughal Empire</h2><p>The <strong>Mughal Empire</strong> was one of the largest and most powerful empires in Indian history, ruling from 1526 to 1857. At its peak under <strong>Aurangzeb</strong>, it controlled nearly 4 million km² of territory.</p><h2>Mughal Emperors at a Glance</h2><table><tr><th>Emperor</th><th>Reign</th><th>Key Achievement</th></tr><tr><td>Babur (1st)</td><td>1526-1530</td><td>Founded Mughal Empire; Won Battle of Panipat (1526)</td></tr><tr><td>Humayun (2nd)</td><td>1530-1540, 1555-56</td><td>Lost and regained empire; Father of Akbar</td></tr><tr><td>Akbar (3rd)</td><td>1556-1605</td><td>Greatest Mughal; Din-i-Ilahi; Navratnas in court</td></tr><tr><td>Jahangir (4th)</td><td>1605-1627</td><td>Known for justice; Married Nur Jahan</td></tr><tr><td>Shah Jahan (5th)</td><td>1628-1658</td><td>Built Taj Mahal, Red Fort, Jama Masjid</td></tr><tr><td>Aurangzeb (6th)</td><td>1658-1707</td><td>Largest empire; implemented Sharia; Compiled Fatawa Alamgiri</td></tr></table><div class='highlight-box'><strong>Key Battle:</strong> First Battle of Panipat (1526) — Babur defeated Ibrahim Lodi using gunpowder and artillery for the first time in India. This established Mughal rule.</div><h2>Akbar's Navratnas (Nine Gems)</h2><div class='fact-box'>1. Birbal (Wit & Wisdom)<br>2. Tansen (Music)<br>3. Raja Todar Mal (Finance/Revenue system)<br>4. Raja Man Singh (Military)<br>5. Abul Fazl (Author of Ain-i-Akbari)<br>6. Faizi (Poet)<br>7. Mullah Do Piaza (Advisor)<br>8. Abdul Rahim Khan-i-Khana (Poet)<br>9. Fakir Aziao-Din (Mystic)</div><h2>Mughal Architecture</h2><ul><li>🕌 <strong>Taj Mahal</strong> (Agra) — Shah Jahan (1643)</li><li>🏰 <strong>Red Fort</strong> (Delhi) — Shah Jahan (1648)</li><li>🕌 <strong>Jama Masjid</strong> (Delhi) — Shah Jahan (1656)</li><li>🏰 <strong>Agra Fort</strong> — Akbar (1573)</li><li>🏙️ <strong>Fatehpur Sikri</strong> — Akbar's capital</li><li>🕌 <strong>Humayun's Tomb</strong> — First garden tomb, inspired Taj Mahal</li></ul><h2>Quick Revision Notes</h2><ul><li>Read the definition and write it once in your own words.</li><li>Make a small table of key facts, formulas, dates, or examples related to Mughal Empire: History, Rulers, Culture and Legacy.</li><li>Revise the topic after 24 hours and again before the exam.</li></ul><h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2><ul><li>Do not memorize only headings; understand the reason behind every point.</li><li>Do not mix similar terms, dates, examples, or formulas.</li><li>Do not skip practice questions after reading the explanation.</li></ul><h2>Practice Questions</h2><ol><li>Write a short note on the main idea of this topic.</li><li>List three important facts that can be asked in exams.</li><li>Explain one example in simple language.</li><li>Create five one-line revision points from this article.</li></ol><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><h3>Is this topic important for exams?</h3><p>Yes. This topic is useful for school tests, revision, and competitive exam general awareness depending on the syllabus.</p><h3>How should I revise it quickly?</h3><p>Start with the summary, then revise the table or bullet points, and finally solve two or three practice questions.</p>",
